  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The church in anticipation gives thanks for the judicial revelation of its God, the near approach of which He Himself asserts to it. The connection with ו in וקרוב שׁמך presents a difficulty. Neither here nor anywhere else is it to be supposed that ו is synonymous with כּי; but at any rate even כי might stand instead of it. For Hupfeld's attempt to explain it: and \"near is Thy name\" Thy wonders have declared; and Hitzig's: and Thou whose Name is near, they declare Thy wondrous works - are past remedy. Such a personification of wonders does not belong to the spirit of Hebrew poetry, and such a relative clause lies altogether beyond the bounds of syntax. If we would, however, take וקרוב שׁמך, after ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 50:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as a result of the thanksgiving (Campensis), then that for which thanks are rendered would remain undefined; neither will it do to take קרוב as referring to the being inwardly present (Hengstenberg), since this, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 12:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 30:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), would require some addition, which should give to the nearness this reference to the mouth or to the heart. Thus, therefore, nothing remains for us but to connect the nearness of the Name of God as an outward fact with the earnest giving of thanks. The church has received the promise of an approaching judicial, redemptive revelation of God, and now says, \"We give Thee thanks, we give thanks and near is Thy Name;\" it welcomes the future act of God with heartfelt thanksgiving, all those who belong to it declare beforehand the wonders of God. Such was really the position of matters when in Hezekiah's time the oppression of the Assyrians had reached its highest point - Isaiah's promises of a miraculous divine deliverance were at that time before them, and the believing ones saluted beforehand, with thanksgiving, the \"coming Name of Jahve\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 30:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The כּי which was to be expected after הודינו (cf. e.g., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 100:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) does not follow until ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 75:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". God Himself undertakes the confirmation of the forthcoming thanksgiving and praise by a direct announcement of the help that is hailed and near at hand (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 85:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It is not to be rendered, \"when I shall seize,\" etc., for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 75:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " has not the structure of an apodosis. כּי is confirmatory, and whatever interpretation we may give to it, the words of the church suddenly change into the words of God. מועד in the language of prophecy, more especially of the apocalyptic character, is a standing expression fore the appointed time of the final judgment (vid., on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Habakkuk 2:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). When this moment or juncture in the lapse of time shall have arrived, then God will seize or take possession of it (לקח in the unweakened original sense of taking hold of with energy, cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 18:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 2:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "): He Himself will then interpose and hold judgment according to the strictly observed rule of right (מישׁרים, adverbial accusative, cf. במישׁרים, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 9:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and frequently). If it even should come to pass that the earth and all its inhabitants are melting away (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 14:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 15:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 2:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), i.e., under the pressure of injustice (as is to be inferred from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 75:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), are disheartened, scattered asunder, and are as it were in the act of dissolution, then He (the absolute I, אנכי) will restrain this melting away: He setteth in their places the pillars, i.e., the internal shafts (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 9:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), of the earth, or without any figure: He again asserts the laws which lie at the foundation of its stability. תכּנתּי is a mood of certainty, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 75:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is a circumstantial clause placed first, after the manner of the Latin ablative absolute. Hitzig appropriately compares ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 29:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 23:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " may also be understood according to this bearing of the case.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The utterance of God is also continued after the Sela. It is not the people of God who turn to the enemies with the language of warning on the ground of the divine promise (Hengstenberg); the poet would then have said אמרנוּ, or must at least have said על־כּן אמרתּי. God Himself speaks, and His words are not yet peremptorily condemning, as in Psalm 50:16., cf. Psalm 46:11, but admonitory and threatening, because it is not He who has already appeared for the final judgment who speaks, but He who announces His appearing. With אמרתּי He tells the braggarts who are captivated with the madness of supposed greatness, and the evil-doers who lift up the horn or the head, ",
        "children": [
